1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:02,675
(Acts 9:9).

2
00:00:02,625 --> 00:00:08,075
This statement which I quote in Latin is made in St Luke’s narrative about St Paul.

3
00:00:08,075 --> 00:00:12,662
It records that ‘Paul rose from the ground with open eyes and seeing nothing.

4
00:00:12,662 --> 00:00:15,762
The words are open to four interpretations.

5
00:00:15,762 --> 00:00:24,425
One is, that when he rose up from the ground he was gazing wide-eyed at naught, that naught being God, for the vision of God he would describe as the naught.

6
00:00:24,425 --> 00:00:28,712
Another explanation is that when he got up he saw nothing but God.

7
00:00:28,712 --> 00:00:32,012
The third, he saw naught but God in all things.

8
00:00:32,012 --> 00:00:36,450
The fourth, that in the divine vision he beheld all things as a naught.

9
00:00:36,450 --> 00:00:41,462
He previously tells how light came suddenly from heaven and felled him to the ground.

10
00:00:41,462 --> 00:00:44,762
Mark you, he says that the light came from heaven.

11
00:00:44,762 --> 00:00:49,337
According to our doctors, though heaven is fraught with light it does not shine.

12
00:00:49,337 --> 00:00:52,212
The sun is full of light and shines withal.

13
00:00:52,212 --> 00:00:58,637
Our doctors teach that fire does not give any light in the simple, natural perfection of its highest state.

14
00:00:58,637 --> 00:01:02,512
Its nature is too pure for eye in any wise to see.

15
00:01:02,512 --> 00:01:09,662
So subtle is it, so unlike the eye, that were it here below within our view it could not stimulate our eyes to sight.

16
00:01:09,662 --> 00:01:16,362
And yet, forsooth, we see it is absorbed by different things, such as a lump of coal, a piece of wood.

17
00:01:16,362 --> 00:01:21,975
By the light of heaven we see the light that is God whereto no mind of man is able to attain.

18
00:01:21,975 --> 00:01:26,812
As St Paul hath it: ‘God dwells in a light that no man can approach unto.

19
00:01:26,812 --> 00:01:29,787
He says, ‘God is light inaccessible.

20
00:01:29,787 --> 00:01:32,062
There is no admittance to God.

21
00:01:32,062 --> 00:01:38,325
No man still on the ascent, still on the increase in grace and in light, has ever yet got into God.

22
00:01:38,325 --> 00:01:41,925
God is no crescent light: we get to him by growing.

23
00:01:41,925 --> 00:01:44,787
In the growing process God is unseen.

24
00:01:44,787 --> 00:01:48,487
When God is seen it is in the light that is God himself.

25
00:01:48,487 --> 00:01:52,962
A master says, In God there is no more nor less nor this nor that.

26
00:01:52,962 --> 00:01:55,500
Whiles we are on the way we are not there.

27
00:01:55,500 --> 00:01:59,112
He says, ‘A light from heaven shone round about him.

28
00:01:59,112 --> 00:02:02,050
Implying the capture of his entire soul.

29
00:02:02,050 --> 00:02:14,812
A master says that in this light all the soul-powers are exalted and raised to a higher power, the outward senses we see and hear with as well as the inner senses we call thoughts: the reach of these and their profundity are most amazing.

30
00:02:14,812 --> 00:02:18,837
I can think as easily about things overseas as close at hand.

31
00:02:18,837 --> 00:02:21,975
Above thought comes the intellect, as seeker.

32
00:02:21,975 --> 00:02:26,712
She goes about looking, casting her net here and there, gaining and losing.

33
00:02:26,712 --> 00:02:34,275
Above intellect the seeker there is another intellect which does not seek but rests in its pure and simple essence in the realm of light.

34
00:02:34,275 --> 00:02:38,500
And I say it is in this light that all the soul-powers are exalted.

35
00:02:38,500 --> 00:02:40,625
Senses rise to thoughts.

36
00:02:40,625 --> 00:02:45,812
How high, how fathomless these are, that no one knows except God and the soul.

37
00:02:45,812 --> 00:03:01,462
Our theologians teach, and it is a knotty question, that angels know nothing about thoughts unless the thoughts take wing and rise up into intellect—intellect the seeker; and this intellect, the seeker, soars up into the intellect which does not seek, which is the pure light in itself.

38
00:03:01,462 --> 00:03:04,700
This light embraces all the powers of the soul.

39
00:03:04,700 --> 00:03:08,475
Accordingly he says, ‘The heavenly light encircled him.

40
00:03:08,475 --> 00:03:14,187
One master lays it down that anything which has an emanation is exempt from these lower things.

41
00:03:14,187 --> 00:03:18,275
God emanates into all creatures without being affected by any.

42
00:03:18,275 --> 00:03:19,862
He does not need them.

43
00:03:19,862 --> 00:03:23,575
God energises nature and her first work is the heart.

44
00:03:23,575 --> 00:03:30,262
Wherefore some doctors would pretend the soul is altogether in the heart and flows thereout as life into the other members.

45
00:03:30,262 --> 00:03:31,400
Not so.

46
00:03:31,400 --> 00:03:34,062
The soul is in each member, whole.

47
00:03:34,062 --> 00:03:36,850
True, her chief work is in the heart.

48
00:03:36,850 --> 00:03:44,137
The heart being in the middle gets protection on all sides, just as heaven is protected from outside influence and intrusion.

49
00:03:44,137 --> 00:03:46,162
It contains all things.

50
00:03:46,162 --> 00:03:49,637
It moves all things and itself remains unmoved.

51
00:03:49,637 --> 00:03:55,050
Not even fire, exalted though it be in its most high estate, can lick the heavens.

52
00:03:55,204 --> 00:04:02,316
In the encircling light he fell to earth, and his eyes being unsealed he, open-eyed, beheld all things as naught.

53
00:04:02,266 --> 00:04:05,966
And beholding all things as naught he was beholding God.

54
00:04:05,966 --> 00:04:13,766
Mark here what the soul says in the Book of Love: ‘By night in my bed I sought him my soul loveth: I sought him and I found him not.

55
00:04:13,766 --> 00:04:20,154
She sought him in her bed: meaning to convey that anyone cleaving to aught below God has too narrow a lie.

56
00:04:20,154 --> 00:04:23,441
God’s entire creation is all too confined.

57
00:04:23,441 --> 00:04:26,266
Quoth she, ‘I sought him all night through.

58
00:04:26,266 --> 00:04:30,166
There is no night without the light: only, it is veiled.

59
00:04:30,166 --> 00:04:33,766
The sun is shining in the night albeit screened from view.

60
00:04:33,766 --> 00:04:37,316
By day it shines, eclipsing all the other lights.

61
00:04:37,316 --> 00:04:41,404
So does the light of God; it blinds and puts out any light.

62
00:04:41,404 --> 00:04:44,804
Our creaturely expectations, all these are night.

63
00:04:44,804 --> 00:04:50,354
What I mean to say is, that nothing we find in a creature is more than a shadow and dark.

64
00:04:50,354 --> 00:04:55,429
Even the highest angel’s light, exalted though it be, illumines not the soul.

65
00:04:55,429 --> 00:04:58,654
All but the first light is darkness, is night.

66
00:04:58,654 --> 00:05:00,854
By it she cannot find God.

67
00:05:00,854 --> 00:05:05,441
I rose and sought him all about, I scoured the broadways and the alleys.

68
00:05:05,441 --> 00:05:11,554
The watchmen (angels) found me, and I questioned them, “Saw ye not him whom my soul loveth?

69
00:05:11,554 --> 00:05:15,629
But they answered not; peradventure they could not apprehend him.

70
00:05:15,629 --> 00:05:19,616
It was but a little that I passed and I found him my soul loveth.

71
00:05:19,616 --> 00:05:24,816
The little, the trifle, that she missed him by has often been the burden of my teaching.

72
00:05:24,816 --> 00:05:30,816
He to whom mortal things are not all trivial and as naught withal, that man shall not find God.

73
00:05:30,816 --> 00:05:35,254
Having passed by a little,’ she says, ‘I found him whom I sought.

74
00:05:35,254 --> 00:05:43,779
When God pours into and informs the soul and thou takest him as a light or a state or a boon, whatsoever thou knowest about him, that God is not.

75
00:05:43,779 --> 00:05:48,879
We have to transcend the little, discard the adventitious and perceive God one.

76
00:05:48,879 --> 00:05:53,391
She says, ‘When I had passed by a little I found him my soul loveth.

77
00:05:53,391 --> 00:05:56,766
We are very fond of saying, ‘him my soul loveth.

78
00:05:56,766 --> 00:06:00,654
But he is far away above the soul, nor does she name her love.

79
00:06:00,654 --> 00:06:03,529
There are five reasons why she names him not.

80
00:06:03,529 --> 00:06:05,741
One is that God is nameless.

81
00:06:05,741 --> 00:06:08,979
Any name she gave him would have to be well chosen.

82
00:06:08,979 --> 00:06:12,266
God is beyond all name, none can express him.

83
00:06:12,266 --> 00:06:18,554
A second reason is that on swooning away into God for love, the soul is conscious of nothing but love.

84
00:06:18,554 --> 00:06:22,054
She fondly imagines that everyone knows him like that.

85
00:06:22,054 --> 00:06:26,104
She is amazed that any wight should find him aught but love alone.

86
00:06:26,104 --> 00:06:28,941
Thirdly, she has no time to name him.

87
00:06:28,941 --> 00:06:32,404
Love does not leave her any time to use another word.

88
00:06:32,404 --> 00:06:36,379
Fourthly, perchance she weens he has no other name than love.

89
00:06:36,379 --> 00:06:38,954
In love she pronounces all names.

90
00:06:38,954 --> 00:06:43,491
Quoth she, ‘I rose up, I went through the broad streets and the alleys.

91
00:06:43,491 --> 00:06:47,079
And when I had passed a little I found him my soul loveth.

92
00:06:47,236 --> 00:06:50,998
Paul rose from the ground wide-eyed, beholding nothing.

93
00:06:50,948 --> 00:06:53,011
I cannot see what is one.

94
00:06:53,011 --> 00:06:55,773
He saw nothing, to wit, God.

95
00:06:55,773 --> 00:06:57,936
God is naught and God is one.

96
00:06:57,936 --> 00:07:00,111
What aught is is naught as well.

97
00:07:00,111 --> 00:07:02,536
What God is is he altogether.

98
00:07:02,536 --> 00:07:15,211
As Dionysius says about the light: speaking of God he says, He is supernatural, supervital, superluminous; he will allow him neither this nor that, but makes him out to be I know not what that far transcends them.

99
00:07:15,211 --> 00:07:21,773
Aught seen, aught that may come within thy ken, that God is not; for why, God is not this nor that.

100
00:07:21,773 --> 00:07:25,536
Whoever says that God is here or there, credit him not.

101
00:07:25,536 --> 00:07:28,448
The light which God is shines in darkness.

102
00:07:28,448 --> 00:07:33,836
God is the true light: to see it one has to be blind and strip God naked of things.

103
00:07:33,836 --> 00:07:39,898
A master says, To argue about God from any sort of likeness is to argue falsely about him.

104
00:07:39,898 --> 00:07:44,086
But to argue about God from naught is to argue soundly withal.

105
00:07:44,086 --> 00:07:52,098
When the soul is reduced to one and is gotten therein by discarding herself altogether, there she finds God, as it were, in a naught.

106
00:07:52,098 --> 00:08:01,436
It appeared to one soul as in a dream (it was a waking dream), to be big with naught like a woman with child, and in this naught God was born, the fruits of the naught.

107
00:08:01,436 --> 00:08:03,423
God was born in the naught.

108
00:08:03,423 --> 00:08:08,248
Therefore he says, ‘He arose from the earth wide-eyed, gazing at naught.

109
00:08:08,248 --> 00:08:11,336
He had a vision of God where there are no creatures.

110
00:08:11,336 --> 00:08:16,073
He beheld all creatures as naught for he had the whole essence of creatures in him.

111
00:08:16,073 --> 00:08:18,473
He is the all-containing essence.

112
00:08:18,473 --> 00:08:21,748
Another thing he means by saying, ‘he saw naught.

113
00:08:21,748 --> 00:08:28,573
According to our masters, any perception of externals entails some inroad by them, an impression at the least.

114
00:08:28,573 --> 00:08:37,211
To get some idea of a thing, a stone, for instance, I do (not) take into my mind the grossest part of it; that I leave outside.

115
00:08:37,211 --> 00:08:43,861
As it exists in the ground of my soul where it is at its noblest and best, it is merely a type (or idea).

116
00:08:43,861 --> 00:08:53,848
Things perceived by my soul from without contain an outside element: my perception of creature in God contains nothing but God alone, for in God there is nothing but God.

117
00:08:53,848 --> 00:08:56,473
When I see all creatures I see not.

118
00:08:56,473 --> 00:08:58,973
He saw God where creatures are not.

119
00:08:58,973 --> 00:09:01,761
In the third place, why he saw naught.

120
00:09:01,761 --> 00:09:03,211
Naught was God.

121
00:09:03,211 --> 00:09:08,923
A master says, Creatures in God are as naught for he has in him the whole essence of creatures.

122
00:09:08,923 --> 00:09:11,811
He is the being that contains all beings.

123
00:09:11,811 --> 00:09:18,398
The master says, Nothing inferior to God, however nigh it might be to him, but has some alien taint.

124
00:09:18,398 --> 00:09:22,473
The master says an angel knows himself and God without means.

125
00:09:22,473 --> 00:09:28,573
Into other things he knows there comes an outside element, some interference still, however slight.

126
00:09:28,573 --> 00:09:33,823
If we are to know God it must be without means, nothing foreign can come in between.

127
00:09:33,823 --> 00:09:40,498
When we do see God in his light it happens in private, safe from the slightest intrusion of creaturely things.

128
00:09:40,498 --> 00:09:43,636
Then we have immediate knowledge of eternal life.

129
00:09:43,636 --> 00:09:45,986
Seeing nothing, he saw God.

130
00:09:45,986 --> 00:09:49,823
The light which is God is flowing and darkening every light.

131
00:09:49,823 --> 00:09:56,473
Concerning it Job says, ‘He commanded the sun not to shine and sealeth up the stars as it were with a seal.

132
00:09:56,473 --> 00:10:09,723
Enveloped in this light he could see naught beside; his whole soul was distraught, intent upon the light that is God to the exclusion of all else; and this is a lesson to us, for what time we are busy with God we mind little what goes on without.

133
00:10:09,844 --> 00:10:15,369
Fourthly, he saw naught since the light which is God is unmixed, free from admixture.

134
00:10:15,319 --> 00:10:19,206
It shows it was the true light he beheld for there was nothing there.

135
00:10:19,206 --> 00:10:23,319
By light he simply means that he saw nothing with his open eyes.

136
00:10:23,319 --> 00:10:26,644
In that he saw not, he saw the divine naught.

137
00:10:26,644 --> 00:10:30,831
St Augustine says, When he saw nothing, he saw God.

138
00:10:30,831 --> 00:10:35,806
According to St Paul, ‘Whoso only seeth being blind, he seeth God.

139
00:10:35,806 --> 00:10:48,469
As St Augustine hath it, ‘God is the true light, preserver of the soul, more nigh to her than she is to herself, and by the same token, when the soul turns her back on things becoming, then God must needs shine into her.

140
00:10:48,469 --> 00:10:52,531
This soul knows neither love nor care, she is unmindful of them.

141
00:10:52,531 --> 00:10:58,344
The soul that fares not forth to outside things comes home to stay in her impartible pure light.

142
00:10:58,344 --> 00:11:01,681
She does not love nor does she fear nor care withal.

143
00:11:01,681 --> 00:11:05,306
Knowledge is the basis, the foundation of all being.

144
00:11:05,306 --> 00:11:08,006
Love has no hold except in knowledge.

145
00:11:08,006 --> 00:11:13,631
When the soul is blind and can see naught beside, then she sees God, it is inevitable.

146
00:11:13,631 --> 00:11:25,269
A master says, the eye at its clearest, without any colour, sees every colour; not just as a colourless thing in itself, but in place in the body it has to be void of all colour for us to see colours.

147
00:11:25,269 --> 00:11:30,331
In colourless things all colours are seen, aye, though it be down in one’s feet.

148
00:11:30,331 --> 00:11:32,694
God is something all-embracing.

149
00:11:32,694 --> 00:11:36,144
For God to be seen by the soul she has to be blind.

150
00:11:36,144 --> 00:11:41,744
Accordingly he says, ‘He saw the naught whose light all lights are, whose being all beings are.

151
00:11:41,744 --> 00:11:47,344
The bride says in the Book of Love: ‘When I had passed by a little I found him my soul loveth.

152
00:11:47,344 --> 00:11:50,269
The little she had passed all creatures were.

153
00:11:50,269 --> 00:11:54,069
Whoso putteth not these behind him shall not find God.

154
00:11:54,069 --> 00:12:00,119
And eke she would imply that however small, however pure a thing I know God by, yet it must go.

155
00:12:00,119 --> 00:12:05,881
Even the light that verily is God, if I take it where it plays upon my soul is foreign to him.

156
00:12:05,881 --> 00:12:07,931
I must take it at the source.

157
00:12:07,931 --> 00:12:13,531
I cannot really see the light that shines upon the wall unless I turn my gaze to where it comes from.

158
00:12:13,531 --> 00:12:17,181
But if I take it in its cause I am robbed of its effect.

159
00:12:17,181 --> 00:12:24,081
I ought to take it neither where it falls nor in its eruption nor yet as brooding in itself; these are all mere modes.

160
00:12:24,081 --> 00:12:29,631
We must take God in modeless mode and unconditioned essence, for he is free from mode.

161
00:12:29,631 --> 00:12:34,819
St Bernard says: He who would know thee, God, must mete thee with no measure.

162
00:12:34,819 --> 00:12:40,256
Please God we may attain that understanding which is wholly without mode and without measure.

163
00:12:40,256 --> 00:12:41,894
So help us God.

164
00:12:41,894 --> 00:12:42,844
Amen.
